00:29:01.300 --> 00:29:03.440
then Colo will have captured the request, right?

00:29:03.600 --> 00:29:05.140
So like the request went to the homepage

00:29:05.840 --> 00:29:06.720
and it returned a 200.

00:29:07.360 --> 00:29:10.220
So that's already like two things we can now turn into code

00:29:10.300 --> 00:29:11.140
in our integration test.

00:29:11.860 --> 00:29:19.180
So first step being, well, I guess this is the act and the assert in the sense that the assert is the 200.

00:29:19.740 --> 00:29:22.160
And then the act is firing off a request to the homepage.

00:29:23.580 --> 00:29:27.840
Now, the tricky bit, and this is where it gets the most fun, is the arrange.

00:29:28.340 --> 00:29:35.180
So if we just put those two things into our test, to imaginary test, there wouldn't have been any to-dos there, right?

00:29:35.320 --> 00:29:36.840
So it's actually not an interesting test yet.

00:29:37.240 --> 00:29:44.560
But in your local version where the trace was recorded, you actually had maybe like three to-dos already in your database.

00:29:45.780 --> 00:29:46.560
Does that make sense so far?

00:29:46.920 --> 00:29:47.660
Yeah, yeah, absolutely.

00:29:49.760 --> 00:29:59.080
So on the homepage, like your to-do app might make a SQL query to like select all the to-dos or all the to-dos for the currently logged in user.

00:30:00.860 --> 00:30:10.100
And then Kolo would store that SQL query, would store that select, and would also store actually what data the database returned.

00:30:10.350 --> 00:30:16.840
This is actually something where, yeah, Kolo goes beyond a lot of the existing kind of like debugging tooling that might exist.

00:30:18.620 --> 00:30:22.800
Like actually showing exactly what data the database returned in a given SQL query.

00:30:24.160 --> 00:30:27.940
But imagine we get like a single to-do return, right?

00:30:29.180 --> 00:30:33.620
We now know that to replicate this like trace in our test,

00:30:34.130 --> 00:30:38.600
we need to start by seeding that to do into the database.

00:30:39.520 --> 00:30:42.160
So that's where like the trace inversion comes in.

00:30:42.640 --> 00:30:47.460
If like a request starts with a select of like the to do table,

00:30:48.120 --> 00:30:50.360
then the first thing that needs to happen in the integration test

00:30:50.820 --> 00:30:56.120
is actually a like creating like an insert into the database for that to do.

00:30:56.820 --> 00:30:58.720
And now when you fire off the request to the homepage,

00:30:58.800 --> 00:31:01.540
it actually goes through your real code path

00:31:01.720 --> 00:31:03.200
where like an actual to-do gets loaded

00:31:03.420 --> 00:31:05.760
and gets printed out onto the page.

00:31:06.040 --> 00:31:08.640
So that's like the most basic kind of example

00:31:08.780 --> 00:31:10.680
of like how can you turn

00:31:10.840 --> 00:31:13.760
like a locally captured trace of a request

00:31:14.460 --> 00:31:15.600
that like made a SQL query

00:31:15.780 --> 00:31:18.820
and returned 200 into like an integration test.

00:31:19.500 --> 00:31:20.440
Yeah, that's awesome.

