00:32:34.820 --> 00:32:36.040
I think in Django world,

00:32:36.120 --> 00:32:39.300
it's reasonably common to write integration tests like this,

00:32:39.560 --> 00:32:41.500
as in like the actual database gets hit.

00:32:42.440 --> 00:32:45.140
You have this idea of like the Django test client,

00:32:45.700 --> 00:32:48.860
which sends like a, you know, real in air quotes,

00:32:49.290 --> 00:32:52.000
HTTP request through the entire Django stack,

00:32:52.580 --> 00:32:54.320
as opposed to doing the more unit test approach.

00:32:54.840 --> 00:32:55.860
So it hits the routes.

00:32:56.020 --> 00:33:00.160
It hits like all the, that sort of stuff all the way.

00:33:00.620 --> 00:33:01.340
And the template.

00:33:02.120 --> 00:33:02.520
Yep.

00:33:03.700 --> 00:33:06.900
And then at the end, you can assert based on like the content of the response,

00:33:07.320 --> 00:33:10.640
or you can check, like, imagine if we go back to the to-do example,

00:33:11.940 --> 00:33:17.200
if we're testing like the add to-do endpoint or form submission,

00:33:17.900 --> 00:33:20.880
then you could make a, like a database query at the end.

00:33:21.200 --> 00:33:22.560
And Colo actually does this as well,

00:33:22.690 --> 00:33:25.860
because like, again, we know like that you inserted a to do

00:33:25.990 --> 00:33:28.760
in your request, so we can actually make an assert.

00:33:29.100 --> 00:33:31.200
This is a different example of the trace inversion.

00:33:31.940 --> 00:33:34.340
If there's an insert in your request that you captured,

00:33:35.020 --> 00:33:38.060
then we know at the end of the integration test,

00:33:38.110 --> 00:33:41.000
we want to assert that this row now exists in the database.

00:33:42.600 --> 00:33:45.960
So yeah, you can assert at the very end to say,

00:33:47.880 --> 00:33:50.200
does this row actually exist in the database now?

00:33:50.320 --> 00:33:52.940
So it's a very nice kind of reasonably end-to-end,

00:33:53.840 --> 00:33:54.940
but still integration test.

